{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17636175","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17636175"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:39+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:24:39+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17568"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17568"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71340"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10258"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17568"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"56815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"6909"},{"type":"tags","id":"10059"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23971"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23979"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"71340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/71340"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of glucose absorption from the small intestinal lumen?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Facilitated diffusion via GLUT4","Active transport against sodium gradient","Active transport with sodium via SGLT1","Endocytosis in membrane vesicles","Simple diffusion across the membrane"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EGlucose absorption from the intestinal lumen occurs via \u003Cstrong\u003Eactive transport with sodium via SGLT1\u003C/strong\u003E (sodium-dependent glucose cotransporter 1) on the luminal membrane of enterocytes. This process uses the sodium gradient maintained by sodium-potassium ATPase on the basolateral membrane. Glucose then exits the cell via GLUT2 transporters on the basolateral membrane.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESimple diffusion across the membrane\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose is too large and polar to diffuse across cell membranes without specific transporters\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFacilitated diffusion via GLUT4\u003C/strong\u003E - GLUT4 is primarily found in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue, not intestinal epithelium\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActive transport against sodium gradient\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose transport occurs with sodium, not against it\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndocytosis in membrane vesicles\u003C/strong\u003E - Glucose absorption does not involve vesicular transport\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis sodium-dependent glucose absorption mechanism is the target of oral rehydration therapy, where sodium and glucose are given together to enhance water absorption in treating diarrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Glucose absorption in the small intestine occurs primarily via sodium-dependent glucose cotransporter 1 (SGLT1) on the luminal membrane.","Glucose exits intestinal epithelial cells via GLUT2 transporters on the basolateral membrane.","This process requires ATP to maintain the sodium gradient that drives glucose absorption."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"ite